metadata.name: BLOTTER #21
metadata.description:
Generative project that combines the creation of visual elements using artificial intelligence and digital collage.
It contains 101 pngs with transparency distributed in 8 different layers, which enables it to generate more than 222 million possible combinations.

metadata.name: Be our voice! #9
metadata.description:
If you look carefully at this work, you will see a map.
This is the map of Iran. A country whose people bravely stand against oppressive forces to revive their violated human rights.
The protests started because of the murder of a girl named Mahsa Amini that was killed by the moral police of Iran because of "improper clothing"!
These days, many Iranian people are deprived of the internet, which is a form of repression by the government to shut down protests and prevent people's voices from reaching the world.
I am also an Iranian and this project is a tribute to the dead of these protests and protesters
Be our voice!

metadata.name: Lineage #166
metadata.description:
Lineage is a collaboration between Tim Maxwell and Twistie that attempts to bridge the gap between traditional and generative art.
256 outputs are generated using 100% JavaScript + p5js, written by Twistie, in the distinctive style of Tim Maxwell. The code tries to replicate not only the style, but also the process and inaccuracies that go into a drawing.

Each iteration has a unique title. 
All 256 rendered outputs and their respective titles will be displayed in high quality on https://twistie.org/lineage. 

10 lucky owners will have their iteration hand drawn and signed. They will each receive the physical 1/1 as well as an NFT version.

Press 's' on keyboard to save in high-res. This is how the art is intended to be viewed.

Hardware acceleration on Chromium-based browsers can impact performance!

metadata.name: September #220
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle “live mode”. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)

metadata.name: Mounds 3 #235
metadata.description:
"Mounds 3" is part of an ongoing series of experiments combining hand-drawn "mounds" and turning them into something unexpected. The p5.js sketch has up to 172 different "mound" illustrations to pick from to build the scene.⁠
⁠
Please be patient. It will take a few seconds for the scene to render; a lot is going on under the hood.⁠ The sketch will load in layers, and the console will log "Done rendering!" when the whole scene is done loading.
⁠
This token was handmade with pens, markers, ink, and p5.js.⁠
⁠
I drew these squiggles between August 29th - September 6th, 2022, with a combination of pens, markers, and brushes in various sketchbooks. The sketches are scanned and separated in Photoshop.⁠

I hope you enjoy this mint as much as I did making it! See https://natenolting.com/2022/09/06/mounds-3/ for more details on this project.

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: scale to print size @ 3000px x 3000px

metadata.name: City Pop - AI Study II #150
metadata.description:
City Pop takes you to a lively and geometric city created by digital architects. The use of shapes, colors, and lines causes visionary hallucinations leading the viewer to imaginary places filled with endless possibilities.

This project is a generative art experiment using a Text2Code workflow. The JavaScript code for this project was written entirely by AI using GPT-3. None of the code was altered or created by a human aside from changing Math.random() with fxrand().

Text2Code study #2 /// Project CoDexter by @BrainArtLabs

metadata.name: Kinetic Butterfly regen #35
metadata.description:
This code generates a kinetic butterfly regen, An infinite flapping of wings.

Shortcuts: [mouse position] light position, [+][-] or [click and drag] increase de speed of rotation, [click] change the direction, [p] print a .png in 4x your screen resolution.

metadata.name: Unendlichkeitsmaschine #442
metadata.description:
An exercise in infinity, recursion and transformation of form. A shape is drawn, sampled, transformed and repeated until the view of it is lost in infinity.

Made with p5js.

Double click to download
Add ?highres=true to the URL to get a higher resolution output

metadata.name: Twistings #79
metadata.description:
✧ TWISTINGS ✧

Twistings, the "Explore Variety" collection, explores the beauty & variety that is hidden within the simple math of Archimedean spirals.

There are seven different circular "entities", each brought forward by using slightly different mathematical settings of the spiral formulas: Drops, Circles, Fireworks, Flowers, Roses, Spirals & Twisters.

____

✧ CURATED / RANDOM ✧

I love both the concept of a heavily curated set, hand picked by the artist, the best representation / the most beautiful, but also the concept of the larger, random collections showing the variety hidden within the algorithm.

I've therefore also released an "Artist Curated" collection of 7 pieces that I meticulously hand-picked from over 1000 outputs. You can find these on the platform 1stDibs.com/nft (under my name "nadieh"). They represent my favorite for each of the seven unique entities. A free mint of this "Explore Variety" collection will be airdropped to each buyer of a "Curated" piece.

____

✧ OPTIONS ✧

n - Toggle grainy noise on/off (on by default, it's subtle to see)

s - Save the image at the current window size and pixel density

To save a larger image you can add the parameter `&pixeldensity=2` (or another number) to the end of the URL when viewed on the live page. Afterwards press "s" to save the image. The number is the factor with which the width and height are increased w.r.t. the current window size.

-- The larger the image / pixeldensity, the longer it will take to create & save --

____

✧ NOTES ✧

It works best and fastest in Firefox!

As of the drop day there is a browser bug for Chrome on the ARM Apple laptops. It incorrectly visualizes certain color blend modes. The following color palettes are affected: Antique, Camping, Pastel, Prime & Rainbow. I hope/assume this will be fixed soon. 

____

Created by Nadieh Bremer
Twitter & Instagram: @NadiehBremer
Website: VisualCinnamon.com

metadata.name: Stack of Shapes #26
metadata.description:
Inspired by sketches I'd draw in my college notebook during class. This piece uses a hand-drawn stroke style to draw a stack of overlapping shapes. Look closely and see that the lines are made of thousands of tiny dots. Iterations vary by color scheme, background color, line thickness, density, and more, with a small chance of using a rainbow color palette.  
  
Press R to re-run the drawing animation; enter to save the image in high quality. Enjoy!

metadata.name: Tuesday #88
metadata.description: Maybe it's inspired by the marks left by coffee cups in my notebook. Maybe the doodles in that same notebook, often squares and circles, somehow influenced this work. Maybe the Bridget Riley book sitting on the shelf above gently whispered to me when I wasn't looking. Or maybe I just played with an idea and found it pleasing. The only thing I'm certain of – it was definitely a Tuesday.

metadata.name: Wall of Chart #3
Elo #59
Invasion #40
metadata.description:
In September, like many of us, we remembered our school years, told each other about teachers, classmates, classes... And suddenly we realized that both did not like biology at school. And in vain. This is a very interesting and incredibly beautiful science. Inspired by school memories and beautiful infusoria slipper, we created this work.

By the way, some lucky ones can even have faces. Try your luck!

We hope you will have fun.

And one more thing. We would really like there to be more children in this world who will be able to discuss their favorite and unloved lessons. Therefore, 1/3 of the payment from sales will be transferred to the fund "Save the children"
